  "NASA's New Horizons launched in 2006 and flew by Pluto in July 2015, providing the first close-up images.": "",
  "What is a 'dwarf planet'?": "",
  "A rocky body in the asteroid belt exceeding 100 km in diameter that has remained irregularly shaped": "",
  "A celestial body that orbits the Sun, has enough mass for a round shape, but has not cleared its orbital neighborhood": "",
  "A natural satellite gravitationally bound to one of the outer gas or ice giant planets in our solar system": "",
  "A compact rocky world similar in composition to Mercury but scaled down to a much smaller overall diameter": "",
  "The IAU defined dwarf planets in 2006 as bodies that meet two of three planet criteria — the third (clearing the orbit) is not met.": "",
  "What is an 'asteroid'?": "",
  "A diminutive world that orbits the Sun independently and has achieved a roughly spherical shape through self-gravity": "",
  "A bright streak of light produced when a small particle burns up from friction as it enters Earth's atmosphere": "",
  "A small rocky body orbiting the Sun, mostly found in the belt between Mars and Jupiter": "",
  "A fragment of volatile-rich material that has broken off from a cometary nucleus during a close solar approach": "",
  "Asteroids are rocky/metallic remnants from the solar system's formation that never accreted into a planet.": "",
  "What is the 'Kuiper Belt'?": "",
  "A region of icy bodies beyond Neptune's orbit, from about 30-50 AU": "",
  "A dust cloud around the Sun": "",
  "A ring around Saturn": "",
  "A belt of asteroids between Mars and Jupiter": "",
  "The Kuiper Belt is a vast ring of icy objects beyond Neptune, home to Pluto, Eris, Makemake, and Haumea.": "",
  "What is a 'near-Earth object' (NEO)?": "",
  "An asteroid or comet with an orbit that brings it close to Earth's orbit": "",
  "Artificial fragments of spent rocket stages and defunct satellites left in orbit around Earth from past missions": "",
  "Earth's natural satellite, a large rocky body gravitationally locked into a stable orbit at about 384,000 km distance": "",
  "Any natural or artificial body maintained in a gravitational orbit around Earth at various altitudes and inclinations": "",
  "NEOs are asteroids or comets whose orbits bring them within 1.3 AU of the Sun, posing potential impact risks.": "",
  "What is a 'Lagrange point'?": "",
  "The geometric midpoint of an elliptical orbital path around which a celestial body traces its trajectory": "",
  "The aphelion of a solar orbit, where a body reaches its maximum distance from the Sun along its elliptical path": "",
  "A position in space where the gravitational forces of two large bodies balance the centripetal force needed for a small body to orbit with them": "",
  "A theoretical location in space where all gravitational influences cancel out completely, producing true weightlessness": "",
  "Lagrange points (L1-L5) are equilibrium positions where a small body can maintain a stable position relative to two larger bodies.": "",
  "What is the 'scattered disc'?": "",
  "The region of the main asteroid belt closest to Mars, populated primarily by silicate-rich S-type asteroids": "",
  "The collection of icy particles and rocky debris orbiting Saturn within its gravitational Roche limit zone": "",
  "A distant region of icy bodies with highly eccentric orbits, beyond the Kuiper Belt": "",
  "Fragments remaining after a hypothetical planetary collision shattered a once-intact world into countless pieces": "",
  "The scattered disc contains icy objects (like Eris) with tilted, elongated orbits, scattered by Neptune's gravity.": "",
  "What is 'albedo' in the context of asteroids?": "",
  "The time elapsed since an asteroid first solidified from molten material in the early protoplanetary disk": "",
  "The reflectivity of an asteroid's surface — used to estimate size and composition": "",
  "The three-dimensional geometric form of an asteroid, ranging from nearly spherical to highly irregular and elongated": "",
  "The orbital velocity at which an asteroid travels along its path around the Sun, typically measured in km per second": "",
  "Asteroid albedo helps determine composition: metallic asteroids are more reflective than carbon-rich ones.": "",
  "What is 'orbital clearing'?": "",
  "A planet's ability to gravitationally dominate its orbital zone, removing or capturing smaller bodies": "",
  "When an orbit becomes perfectly circular": "",
  "Cleaning debris from a spacecraft's path": "",
  "When clouds clear in orbit": "",
  "Orbital clearing is the third criterion for planet classification — planets must dominate their orbit gravitationally.": "",
  "What is a 'carbonaceous asteroid' (C-type)?": "",
  "A dark, carbon-rich asteroid that is the most common type in the outer asteroid belt": "",
  "An asteroid made of diamonds": "",
  "A metallic asteroid": "",
  "An asteroid from outside the solar system": "",
  "C-type asteroids are dark, carbon-rich objects making up about 75% of known asteroids, common in the outer belt.": "",
  "What is a 'binary asteroid'?": "",
  "An asteroid with two names": "",
  "An asteroid split in half": "",
  "Two asteroids colliding": "",
  "A system of two asteroids orbiting their common center of gravity": "",
  "Binary asteroids are pairs of asteroids gravitationally bound and orbiting each other — about 15% of NEOs are binaries.": "",
  "An astronomer discovers a round object orbiting the Sun at 40 AU with many other icy bodies nearby. Should this be classified as a planet or dwarf planet?": "",
  "Comet — icy objects are always comets": "",
  "Planet — it orbits the Sun and is round": "",
  "Dwarf planet — it hasn't cleared its orbital neighborhood despite being round and orbiting the Sun": "",
  "Asteroid — it's too far from the Sun": "",
  "Even if round and Sun-orbiting, sharing its zone with many other bodies means it hasn't cleared its orbit — so it's a dwarf planet.": "",
  "NASA's DART mission intentionally crashed into asteroid Dimorphos in 2022. What was the purpose?": "",
  "To extract valuable platinum-group metals and rare earth elements from the asteroid's exposed metallic interior": "",
  "To analyze surface samples for biosignatures or microbial fossils that might indicate extraterrestrial biological activity": "",
  "To gather pristine geological specimens from the asteroid's surface for laboratory analysis of mineral compositions": "",
  "To test whether a kinetic impactor could change an asteroid's orbit, as a planetary defense technique": "",
  "DART was the first planetary defense test, successfully altering Dimorphos's orbit around Didymos by 33 minutes.": "",
  "Jupiter's gravity prevents asteroid belt material from forming a planet. If Jupiter didn't exist, would a planet have formed?": "",
  "Definitely not, because the region between Mars and Jupiter contains insufficient raw material regardless of gravitational influence": "",
  "Possibly a small rocky planet, but the total mass of the belt is very small — only ~4% of the Moon's mass": "",
  "A massive gas giant would have coalesced from the abundant hydrogen and helium concentrated in that orbital zone": "",
  "A rocky super-Earth several times more massive than our planet would have accumulated from the belt's material supply": "",
  "Without Jupiter's perturbations, material might have accreted, but the belt's total mass is so low that only a very small body could form.": "",
  "The Dawn mission visited both Vesta and Ceres. It found that Vesta is dry and rocky while Ceres has water ice and organic molecules. What explains this difference?": "",
  "Ceres gravitationally captured a passing comet that deposited its ice and organic material onto the dwarf planet's surface": "",
  "A massive impact early in Vesta's history vaporized all of its original water ice and volatile surface compounds": "",
  "Both Vesta and Ceres accreted from the same region of the protoplanetary disk at identical distances from the Sun": "",
  "Vesta formed closer to the Sun where it was too hot for ice; Ceres formed farther out where ice could condense": "",
  "Vesta and Ceres represent different formation zones: Vesta near the inner belt (dry) and Ceres in the outer belt (ice-rich).": "",
  "Pluto has a large moon, Charon, that is about half its size. The pair are sometimes called a 'double dwarf planet.' Why?": "",
  "Pluto and Charon display identical surface coloring and spectral signatures, suggesting a shared compositional origin": "",
  "Pluto and Charon were both originally classified as full planets before the IAU revised its planetary definitions": "",
  "Astronomers identified Pluto and Charon simultaneously in the same telescopic observation during their initial discovery": "",
  "Charon is so large relative to Pluto that their center of mass (barycenter) lies outside Pluto's surface": "",
  "The Pluto-Charon barycenter is in the space between them, making them more like a binary system than a planet-moon pair.": "",
  "A metallic asteroid is discovered with high concentrations of platinum and gold. A company proposes mining it. What makes metallic asteroids especially valuable?": "",
  "Metallic asteroids tend to orbit on trajectories that bring them significantly closer to Earth than other asteroid types": "",
  "Metallic asteroids retain thin but breathable atmospheric envelopes generated by outgassing from their iron-rich surfaces": "",
  "The strong gravitational fields and smooth metallic surfaces of these asteroids make spacecraft landings far simpler": "",
  "They contain concentrated precious and industrial metals that are rare on Earth's surface": "",
  "M-type (metallic) asteroids are essentially exposed planetary cores, rich in iron, nickel, platinum-group metals, and other valuable elements.": "",
  "Haumea, a dwarf planet in the Kuiper Belt, has an elongated (egg-like) shape and two small moons. What causes its unusual shape?": "",
  "It hasn't achieved hydrostatic equilibrium": "",
  "A recent collision flattened it": "",
  "Its moons pull it into that shape": "",
  "Rapid rotation (about 4 hours) stretches it into an ellipsoid": "",
  "Haumea rotates extremely rapidly (~3.9 hours), causing centrifugal forces to deform it into a triaxial ellipsoid.": "",
  "An asteroid is tracked and found to have a 1-in-1000 chance of hitting Earth in 50 years. What type of asteroid is it classified as?": "",
  "A Trojan asteroid": "",
  "A trans-Neptunian object": "",
  "A potentially hazardous asteroid (PHA)": "",
  "A main-belt asteroid": "",
  "PHAs are near-Earth asteroids with orbits that come within 0.05 AU of Earth's orbit and are large enough to cause damage.": "",
  "The asteroid Bennu was sampled by NASA's OSIRIS-REx mission. The sample contained amino acids and water-bearing minerals. Why is this significant?": "",
  "The presence of amino acids confirms that Bennu harbors active biological processes sustaining living microorganisms today": "",
  "Finding organic molecules on Bennu constitutes definitive proof that intelligent extraterrestrial life exists elsewhere": "",
  "It suggests asteroids may have delivered building blocks of life and water to early Earth": "",
  "The exotic mineral composition found on Bennu demonstrates that it originated in a galaxy beyond the Milky Way": "",
  "Finding organic molecules and hydrated minerals on Bennu supports the theory that asteroids seeded early Earth with water and life precursors.": "",
  "If Pluto were placed in Mars's orbit, would it be reclassified as a planet?": "",
  "Yes — being inside the asteroid belt makes it a planet": "",
  "Yes — proximity to the Sun would make it a planet": "",
  "No — once a dwarf planet, always a dwarf planet": "",
  "Likely no — Pluto still wouldn't have enough mass to gravitationally clear Mars's orbital neighborhood": "",
  "Planet classification depends on clearing the orbit. Pluto's small mass (0.2% of Earth's) likely couldn't dominate even Mars's zone.": ""
